Functional load and sound change

This R Notebook contains a walk-through of my work to predict sound changes. For a written version, see Chapter 3 of my dissertation.

1. Introduction

There is a long-term debate in Historical Linguistics on whether sound change can be predicted given the distribution of the sounds in the lexicon. The Functional Load Hypothesis (King 1967) states that the likelihood of a neutralization (aka merger) between two sounds is (inversely) proportional to how their contrast is important in a language.

The functional load of a sound pair can be measured by counting the number of word pairs whose distinction relies on that contrast (aka minimal pairs), or by using other measures of informativity, like entropy loss.

In my work, I collected a dataset of mergers in different languages to investigate the hypothesis, using corpora from CHILDES, CELEX and other public repositories. I present an analysis of the dataset here, using the R libraries tidyverse and lme4.

2. The dataset

Here is a quick look at the dataset.

library(tidyverse)
data = read_csv('fl_data.csv')
head(data)

There are 116 entries for which the following information is available:

  1. Pair: the pair of sounds being observed
  2. Language: the language in which the pair is found
  3. Type: this is a name used to refer to the merger class
  4. Merged: binary variable distinguishing pairs for which a merger is attested in at least one variety of the language (1) versus pairs for which no merger is reported (0)
  5. Enrivonment: it encodes whether the merger happens across the board (Unconditioned) or is conditioned on a specific phonetic enrivonment (Conditioned)
  6. MinPairs: amount of minimal pairs found in the conversational corpora examined associated to the pair
  7. EntropyLoss: entropy loss expected in the language after the merger occurs (multiplied by 1000)
  8. Freq1: frequency of the first sound of the pair
  9. Freq2: frequency of the second sound of the pair

A first question we want to ask is whether minimal pairs and entropy loss are predictors of mergers.

3. Transformations

Before proceeding with the analysis, we log-transform the variables of interest.

  1. LogMinPairs: log-transformed MinPairs
  2. LogEntropyLoss: log-transformed EntropyLoss
data <- data %>% 
  group_by(Type) %>%
  mutate(LogMinPairs=log(MinPairs+1)) %>%
  mutate(LogEntropyLoss=log(EntropyLoss+1))

4. Analysis

4.1 Logistic Regression

A simple way of testing functional load is seeing whether minimal pairs or entropy loss are predictors of mergers. Wedel et al. (2013) propose to use a mixed-effect logistic regression model with minimal pairs and entropy loss as fixed effects, and merger type as a random effect, in order to account for the fact that different merger types can yield different numbers of minimal pairs and entropy (for instance, vowel and consonant mergers are expected to behave differently). We can replicate their analysis by using the glmer() function in the lme4 library.

4.1.1 Minimal Pairs

We can visualize the relationship between minimal pairs and mergers using a boxplot through ggplot2.

First, we create a categorical version of the dependent variable for visualization purposes.

data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Merged_categorical=ifelse(Merged, 'Merged', 'Unmerged'))

Then, we use a boxplot to compare, for each merger set, the number of minimal pairs associated to actual mergers versus unmerged pairs. The graph shows us indeed that the number of minimal pairs for mergers is lower, on average, than that for sound pairs that do not merge.

ggplot(data, aes(x=Merged_categorical,y=LogMinPairs, color=Merged_categorical))+
  geom_boxplot(show.legend=FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~Type) +
  labs(title="Minimal pairs and mergers", x ="", y = "MinPairs") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

The result is confirmed by the logistic regression analysis:

library(lme4)
m1 = glmer(Merged ~ LogMinPairs + (1|Type), family=binomial, data=data)
summary(m1)
## Generalized linear mixed model fit by maximum likelihood (Laplace

##  Family: binomial  ( logit )

The number of minimal pairs turns out to be slightly significant, with z=-2.506 and p=0.0122. The minus sign is also correct: the presence of minimal pairs inhibits mergers.

4.1.2 Entropy

At first sight, the graph seems to be similar for entropy, even though there are several case where entropy is actually higher for the sound pairs for which a merger is attested:

ggplot(data, aes(x=Merged_categorical, LogEntropyLoss, color=Merged_categorical)) +
  geom_boxplot(show.legend=FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~Type) +
  labs(title="Entropy loss and mergers", x ="", y = "Entropy Loss") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

In fact, if we run a logistic regression analysis, the effect is not significant: we have z=-0.048 and p=0.9619.

m2 = glmer(Merged ~ LogEntropyLoss + (1|Type), family=binomial, data=data)

4.2 Conditioned and Unconditioned mergers

A generalization that emerges from my dissertation is that while all mergers which are Unconditioned, aka they occur across the board, are compatible with the Functional Load Hypothesis, Conditioned mergers seem to often violate the hypothesis.

4.2.1 Unconditioned mergers

We can visualize this asymmetry by first isolating Unconditioned mergers, and visualizing their minimal pair counts using the boxplot:

unconditioned = data %>%
  filter(Environment == 'Unconditioned')

ggplot(unconditioned, aes(x=Merged_categorical,y=LogMinPairs,color=Merged_categorical))+
  geom_boxplot(show.legend=FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~Type) +
  labs(title="Minimal pairs and unconditioned mergers", x ="", y = "LogMinPairs") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Almost all the cases seem to show a functional load effect.

This result is confirmed by the fact that in spite of the reduced sample size, the mixed-effect model shows that the LogMinPairs coefficient is still significant:

m3 = glmer(Merged ~ LogMinPairs + (1|Type), family=binomial, data=unconditioned)
summary(m3)

Even though the statistical power is reduced, the number of minimal pairs is even more significant than our previous analysis! We have z=-3.150 and p=0.00163.

4.2.2 Conditioned mergers

Conversely, a look at the conditioned mergers reveals that none of them show functional load effects when looking at minimal pairs:

conditioned = data %>%
  filter(Environment == 'Conditioned')

ggplot(conditioned, aes(x=Merged_categorical,y=LogMinPairs, color=Merged_categorical))+
  geom_boxplot(show.legend=FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~Type) +
  labs(title="Minimal pairs and conditioned mergers", x ="", y = "LogMinPairs") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

This is confirmed by the statistical analysis, for which the LogMinPairs coefficient becomes not significant, and is also associated to the opposite sign, which means that, if anything, we are having an anti-functional load effect!

m4 = glmer(Merged ~ LogMinPairs + (1|Type), family=binomial, data=conditioned)
summary(m4)

5. Conclusions

The analysis shows that functional load is a factor in sound change, but only when the sound changes are unconditioned. If the sound change neutralizes a contrast only in a specific environment, functional load does not seem to be a relevant factor. This finding has important consequences for sound change, but also for language acquisition.

For more information on the topic, check my dissertation, or this summary article that appeared on PWPL.
